Project Report – PubMed Research Paper Filter Tool

Name: Bejjipuram Deepika

1. Objective:
To build a Python-based command-line tool that fetches research papers from PubMed based on a user query, identifies papers with at least one non-academic author (from pharmaceutical or biotech companies), and exports the filtered results to a CSV file.

2. Tools & Technologies Used:

  • Python 3.10

  • Poetry for dependency management

  • Git and GitHub for version control

  • Libraries: requests, pandas, typer, beautifulsoup4

  • ChatGPT for technical guidance and design suggestions

3. Methodology:

  • Accept a query string from the user through the command line.

  • Use the PubMed Entrez API to fetch paper details.

  • Extract metadata such as PubMed ID, title, publication date, authors, affiliations, and emails.

  • Apply heuristics to determine if any author is from a non-academic institution. These include checking for:

    • Absence of terms like "university", "institute", "college", "lab"

    • Presence of keywords like "pharma", "biotech", "inc", "ltd"

  • Save the filtered results to a CSV file with the following columns:

    • PubmedID

    • Title

    • Publication Date

    • Non-academic Author(s)

    • Company Affiliation(s)

    • Corresponding Author Email

4. Results:
A sample query with "cancer" fetched 100 papers. From these, 2 papers included at least one non-academic author. Results are saved to results.csv.

5. Output Sample (from CSV):
